                    <item>
              <title>Call Cloud: Ideas in Mobile Learning, Symposium 6th - 7th March 2014, Watershed, Bristol UK</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8498</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8498</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<h3>Organised by <a href="http://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloudscape/view/2435" target="_blank">Designing for Digital Learners</a> (D4DL) Research Group. This event is supported by QR (Quality Research) funds from <a href="http://www.uwe.ac.uk/" target="_blank">UWE Bristol</a></h3>
<h4>Now closed to new submission</h4>
<h3>BIIML 2014 Programme now available: <a href="http://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8540" target="_blank">http://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8540</a></h3>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The <strong>Ideas in Mobile Learning symposium</strong> invites either 'ideas' abstracts or 'ideas' for the mobiLearnFest component of the Symposium around the broad themes of &lsquo;innovation, creativity and sustainability&rsquo;&nbsp;for <a href="http://www.londonmobilelearning.net/#theory.php?state=0" target="_blank">mobile learning</a>. However, we have a strong preference that papers address at least one of the following three trends of mobile learning state-of-the-art research (<a href="http://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8501" target="_blank">click here for details</a>):</p>
<ul>
<li>Focus on new patterns of connected social learning and work-based practices.</li>
<li>Focus on designing for &lsquo;mobile learning&rsquo; at scale.</li>
<li>Focus on the boundaries of learning that the &lsquo;m&rsquo; in m-learning forces us to explore.</li>
</ul>
<p>The symposium is a research off-shoot of the successful workshop &lsquo;<a href="http://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8434" target="_blank">Towards sustainable mobile learning scenarios</a>&rsquo; held in Bristol 9<sup>th</sup>-10<sup>th</sup> October, 2013. Requested contributions should offer any combination of conceptual, critical, design, empirical, theoretical or experimental work that relates in some way to the symposium&rsquo;s broad themes and/or the three trends. Places are limited to 40 participants in order to enable a single track event where engaging, interdisciplinary conversational threads will be centre stage.</p>
<p>The&nbsp;online space for the Symposium can be reached by clicking <a href="http://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloudscape/view/2896" target="_blank">here</a></p>
<h3><strong>Keynote</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://celstec.org.uk/user/25" target="_blank">Marcus Specht</a>, Co-ordinator&nbsp;<a href="http://celstec.org.uk/" target="_blank">CELSTEC</a> Laboratories, Open University of the Netherlands</li>
</ul>
