                    <item>
              <title>Mark Johnstone: scenario (mobile learning and second language vocabulary development)</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/7772</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/7772</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<h3 dir="ltr">Yezin&rsquo;s Engineering Odyssey</h3>
<p><strong id="internal-source-marker_0.06367512908764184">Yezin lives in Riyadh and is hoping to study engineering at university. He is in a preparatory year program that includes instruction in English, math and science. Yezin has difficulty reading the articles he is given and is specially worried about the technical vocabulary.&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><strong id="internal-source-marker_0.06367512908764184">Yezin&rsquo;s English teacher suggests that he try using a social-network based glossary application on his phone. First, he scans the article he is reading with his learning set and saves it to text. Then he uses the application to identify several words and enters them into his personal glossary. He tags two words using pre-configured tags and creates his own tag for a third. Using concordance software he finds examples of these new words in the British National Corpus and compares these to his own text. He writes a provisional definition for the word and saves it to his learning space. <br /><br />Later, Yezin scans another text and finds his previously entered words highlighted in the new text. He remembers two of these but has forgotten what the third one meant. He finds it in his glossary, linked to the text where he tagged it. He looks there and remembers what it means. Yezin is impressed and tells other people in his learning set about the tool. He thinks that if he can get them to work with him, they will all benefit by sharing their personal glossaries.<br /><br />Using the application, Yezin and his friends have been able to turn an isolated and dull reading task into a social activity. The application not only helps them learn together, but it helps them learn more quickly by connecting prior knowledge to new tasks, and by connecting their individual expertise to that of the group. &nbsp;They also begin to discover shared areas of interest within their field of study and think they might like to collaborate on other levels too.</strong></p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Thu, 24 Jan 2013 09:51:23 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Personas</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/7740</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/7740</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Lauren</strong> is a disabled swimmer with cerebral palsy who has a national classification as competitive swimmer and would like to take some of the e-learning modules on such topics as nutrition and hydration and preparing for competition. The key issues for her are mobility, coordination and sight issues since childhood. In her case self-belief derives from supportive and encouraging parents and the specialist schools. An assessment got her a Macintosh computer and she uses a minidisk recorder and can sometimes claim a taxi to workshops when needed.<br /><br /><strong>George</strong> is a qualified ASA Level 2 teacher with some hearing impairment and wishes to take a Level 2 Coaching course to qualify to work with squad swimmers. &nbsp;He used a note taker for exams - all video clips would required a transcript. In an earlier risk appraisal between the club and pool operator a number of fire alarms required the addition of a flashing light and a policy of informing the duty manager when poolside was adopted so that staff - the lifeguard in particular, understood the aural signalling alone might not be adequate.<br /><br /><strong>Emma</strong> is a competitive squad athlete interested in working &lsquo;poolside&rsquo; as a teacher who is dyslexic - they know from a positive college experience that overlays, or her choices of font colours and backgrounds goes a long way to solve the problems. Her Line Manager, the Head Coach, is aware of the value of providing her with swimming schedules printed on coloured sheets of paper.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 23 Jan 2013 12:13:20 +0000</pubDate>
